{"user_message": {"title": "Security Scan Report — ai-bookkeeper — 2026-05-27", "content": "## Security Scan Report — ai-bookkeeper\n**Date:** 2026-05-27  |  **Stack:** React / Next.js 16  |  **Scope:** `src/**`, `package.json`/`package-lock.json`  |  **Baseline scan** (memory was empty — no prior findings to dedupe)\n\n### Summary by severity\n| Severity | Count |\n|---|---|\n| Critical | 0 |\n| High | 1 |\n| Medium | 1 |\n| Low | 1 |\n\n**Coverage:** All three phases ran (dependency audit ✅, secret detection ✅, code-pattern analysis ✅). The app is currently **frontend-only** — no API routes (`src/app/api` absent), no server handlers, no `fetch`/network calls, no `console` logging of data, and no `localStorage`/`zustand persist`. That meaningfully limits today's attack surface, but the integration secrets staged in `.env.example` (Plaid, Stripe, Twilio, Gemini) signal that server-side intake is coming — findings below are framed for that trajectory.\n\n---\n### 🔴 HIGH\n**H-1 — Unsafe numeric coercion of untrusted amounts** · `src/features/ledger/lib/amount.ts:73,77`\nAfter stripping `[$,\\s]`, `Number(cleaned)` accepts JS numeric literals that are not money: verified `\"1e5\"→100000`, `\"0x10\"→16`, `\"0b11\"→3`. All pass the range (`≤ MAX_AMOUNT` 1,000,000) and decimal checks, so a garbled/adversarial **SMS or OCR** body silently becomes a plausible mid-range transaction. Large mis-parses are bounded by `out-of-range`, but mid-range ones are not. Ranked High (not Medium) because the input is untrusted and the corrupted value is written straight into the financial ledger.\n*Remediation:* validate shape before coercion —\n`if (!/^\\d+(\\.\\d{1,2})?$/.test(cleaned)) return { ok: false, error: \"not-a-number\" };`\nThis also subsumes the `too-many-decimals` / `not-a-number` string paths. Land before the live SMS/OCR adapter (ADR-0001 task 5) routes untrusted strings here.\n\n---\n### 🟠 MEDIUM\n**M-1 — Dependency: PostCSS XSS advisory (GHSA-qx2v-qp2m-jg93)** · `package